disasters. Either the Bush administration refused to exercise authority, was thwarted in the attempt to exercise authority, or wielded authority but could not meet the test of legitimacy needed to enact their goals. Ultimately, the vaunted White House discipline gave way to public recriminations among key advisers. Condemned for secretiveness, the Bush administration became one of the most closely scrutinized presidencies in the modern era.Roberts links the collapse of the Bush presidency to deeper currents in American politics and culture, especially a new militarism and the supremacy of the Reagan-era consensus on low taxes, limited government, and free markets. Only in this setting was it possible to have a “total war on terrorism” in which taxes were reduced, private consumption was encouraged, and businesses were lightly regulated.A balanced, incisive account by a skilled observer of U.S. government, The Collapse of Fortress Bush turns the spotlight from the powerful cabal that launched the war in Iraq to tell a much more disturbing story about American power and the failure of executive leadership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAuthority. 0aExecutive powerzUnited States. 0aPolitical leadershipzUnited States. 0aSeptember 11 Terrorist Attacks, 2001. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh  aBush.  aCollapse.  aFortress.  aargue.  abalanced.  abehavior.  aconstraints.  acounterintuitive.  acurrent.  afederal.  agives.  agovernment.  amany.  ashape.  astructural.  athat.  aview.  awould.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081477606340uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814777336.001.000140uhttps://www.degr